{"parentUuid":"bbb2cff6-f6b5-42eb-9874-ab961403c8ef","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0fbc342a4e25e60d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcsKBURHquPRXVp2Y6cgx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CwDRskmWH6Bpfca4mf2PBc","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\tests\\test_dast_context_documented.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9441,"cache_read_input_tokens":64867,"output_tokens":492,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9441},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":492,"cache_read_input_tokens":64867,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9441,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":9441,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcsKBTWUNYRYQ1yyf2TsS","attributionAgent":"planning","attributionSkill":"pipeline-orchestration","type":"assistant","uuid":"4f157fcf-8f84-4b39-994f-4291db7a427f","timestamp":"2026-07-09T23:00:16.868Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"bbb2cff6-f6b5-42eb-9874-ab961403c8ef","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"895b7771-0494-4fd1-9c42-d5085f2ef142","agentId":"a0fbc342a4e25e60d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QMDftF1pb5ZSHMT9NAq5BH","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Plan — per-customer metric quotas\n2\t\n3\tAuthoritative brief: `.pipeline/requirements.md` (operator-elicited; Resolved / Open / Out-of-scope).\n4\tEvery Resolved item below is turned into scope + an acceptance criterion; the single Open item\n5\t(PUT latency budget) is carried as an Open Question with a stated default; Out-of-scope items are\n6\thard exclusions and are **not** planned. Design source: none (backend HTTP API — no UI to build).\n7\t\n8\t## Summary\n9\t\n10\tMeterly already ingests metered events idempotently (`POST /v1/events`) and rolls them into an\n11\thourly per-tenant counter (`usage_rollup`). This feature adds an **admin-set, per-customer,\n12\tper-metric usage cap** enforced against that existing hourly rollup. Two surfaces change:\n13\t\n14\t1. **`PUT /v1/quotas`** (new, admin-scoped) upserts a cap `(customer_id, metric) → limit_per_window`\n15\t   for the caller's own tenant (201 create / 200 replace, echoing the stored row).\n16\t2. **`POST /v1/events`** (existing) now rejects an event with **429 `quota_exceeded`** when the\n17\t   current-hour rollup `R` plus the incoming quantity `Q` would exceed the cap `L` (`R + Q > L`);\n18\t   customers with no quota row stay unlimited (no behavior change).\n19\t\n20\tThe core approach is **enforce against the value that already exists** — the hourly rollup — rather\n21\tthan introduce any new aggregation, and to make the check **atomic with the rollup increment inside\n22\tthe request's existing transaction** so usage can never exceed `L` under concurrency. The chosen\n23\tserialization mechanism is a `SELECT … FOR UPDATE` row lock on the quota row (details and rejected\n24\talternatives in *Backend* below). One expand-only Alembic migration adds the `quotas` table and an\n25\t`api_keys.scope` column; no new cloud infrastructure is provisioned. The scanner/auth context stays\n26\tthe existing `Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` split-token (relevant to DAST\n27\treadiness, below).\n28\t\n29\t## Stack notes\n30\t\n31\tAssessed each default against this project; every choice **endorses the existing Meterly stack**\n32\trecorded in `CLAUDE.md` — this is a brownfield increment, so consistency with the established stack\n33\tis the overriding consideration, and each default already fits.\n34\t\n35\t- **Language / framework:** Python 3.12 + FastAPI + async SQLAlchemy `text()` repositories — endorsed\n36\t  (matches every existing module; no reason to diverge for a two-endpoint increment).\n37\t- **Database:** PostgreSQL (RDS) — endorsed. The feature leans on two Postgres-specific guarantees the\n38\t  codebase already relies on: `INSERT … ON CONFLICT` upserts and `SELECT … FOR UPDATE` row locking.\n39\t  Both are proven, boring, well-understood primitives (DDIA: prefer a single-node transactional store\n40\t  with real row locks over inventing a distributed counter) — no new datastore is warranted.\n41\t- **Migrations:** Alembic — endorsed; one new revision `0003`, expand-only (see *Data / migrations*).\n42\t- **Auth:** existing API-key facade (Argon2id split-token, per-key Tier-2 throttle) — endorsed and\n43\t  **extended** with a `scope` column (`ingest` default, `admin` for quota management). No third-party\n44\t  IdP is introduced (consistent with `CLAUDE.md`). Admin is modeled as a **superset scope**: an\n45\t  `admin` key may do everything an `ingest` key does *plus* call `PUT /v1/quotas` (rationale in *Auth*).\n46\t- **Cloud / IaC:** AWS + Terraform — **no change**. The feature adds one table and one column to the\n47\t  existing RDS instance; no new AWS service, IAM role, or `infra/` resource. Encryption-at-rest for\n48\t  the new columns is covered by the existing RDS SSE (see *Data classification*). `iac-conventions`\n49\t  therefore not invoked — nothing is provisioned.\n50\t- **Observability / logging:** structlog facade + CloudWatch/X-Ray + Sentry — endorsed; the feature\n51\t  emits three new structured events (see *Logging*).\n52\t- **Runtime secrets:** unchanged — the feature consumes no new credential (`secrets-management` not\n53\t  triggered; DB URL is already fetched at runtime behind the secrets facade).\n54\t\n55\tNothing here recommends *against* a default, so there is no divergence for the checkpoint to ratify —\n56\tonly the confirmation that the brownfield increment stays on the established stack.\n57\t\n58\t## Backend\n59\t\n60\t### The tenant model (why `api_key_id` is the tenant, and what \"admin\" means)\n61\t\n62\tEvery existing table (`events`, `usage_rollup`) is keyed and RLS-isolated by `api_key_id` — in this\n63\tsystem **the api_key *is* the tenant**. The quota model follows suit exactly: a quota row is\n64\t`(api_key_id, customer_id, metric) → limit_per_window`, stored under the authenticated principal's\n65\t`api_key_id`. This is the only model that makes enforcement *bind*: the rollup a `POST /v1/events`\n66\tincrements is keyed by the ingesting key's `api_key_id`, so for a quota to apply to those events its\n67\t`api_key_id` must be that same key. **Admin is therefore a superset scope, not a separate key\n68\tfamily:** a tenant that wants quotas provisions one `admin`-scoped key and uses it to both ingest and\n69\tadminister; `POST /v1/events` accepts any authenticated key (no scope restriction — nothing in the\n70\tbrief restricts ingestion by scope), while `PUT /v1/quotas` requires `scope = 'admin'`.\n71\t\n72\t- *What:* `scope` is a single column on `api_keys` (`'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated), the\n73\t  authenticated principal carries it, and only the quota-management route checks it.\n74\t- *Why this over alternatives:* a **separate `quota_admins` join table or RBAC role table** was\n75\t  rejected — it introduces a many-keys-per-tenant concept the schema does not have and the brief\n76\t  puts out of scope (global/cross-tenant quotas are excluded). A **boolean `is_admin`** was rejected\n77\t  in favor of a `scope` string with a `CHECK (scope IN ('ingest','admin'))` because a string leaves\n78\t  room for future scopes (e.g. `readonly`) without another migration, at no extra cost today.\n79\t- *How it fits:* the same `AuthenticatedPrincipal` that already flows from `require_api_key` (and is\n80\t  cached) simply gains a `scope` field; existing routes ignore it, so their behavior is unchanged.\n81\t- *Tradeoff accepted:* a tenant wanting quotas must ingest with its admin key (single-key-per-tenant).\n82\t  Multi-key-per-tenant is out of scope per the brief; this is consistent with the current schema and\n83\t  flagged, not silently assumed.\n84\t\n85\t### `PUT /v1/quotas` — upsert semantics\n86\t\n87\t- *What:* a new route `src/api/routes/quotas.py` exposing `PUT /v1/quotas`, body\n88\t  `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}`, that upserts the cap and echoes the stored row —\n89\t  **201** on create, **200** on replace. No delete / unset path (out of scope).\n90\t- *Why PUT + upsert (not POST/PATCH):* the resource identity is `(customer_id, metric)` supplied in\n91\t  the body and the operation is **create-or-replace with no partial merge** — that is idempotent\n92\t  replacement, which is precisely PUT's contract (a repeat PUT is a no-op change). POST would imply a\n93\t  new sub-resource each call; PATCH would imply a partial merge we explicitly do not want (the brief\n94\t  says replace, not merge). Idempotent PUT also needs no `Idempotency-Key`.\n95\t- *How create-vs-replace is detected in one statement:* the repository upsert uses\n96\t  `INSERT … ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE … RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted, …`.\n97\t  The `xmax = 0` idiom returns true only when the row was freshly inserted (an `ON CONFLICT` update\n98\t  leaves a non-zero `xmax`), so the service maps `inserted → 201` else `200` **without a second\n99\t  round-trip or a read-before-write race**. (This idiom is documented inline in the repo because a\n100\t  reviewer needs the \"why\".)\n101\t- *Edge stack (unchanged ordering):* the route inherits the middleware stack (security headers, CORS,\n102\t  8 KiB body guard, Tier-1 IP throttle) by being mounted, then composes\n103\t  `require_api_key → enforce_tier2_rate_limit → admin-scope check → handler`, mirroring the\n104\t  `events`/`usage` routes' sibling `_require_authenticated_and_throttled` pattern (kept per-route, not\n105\t  shared, per the existing convention). The scope check raises `HTTPException(403)` → envelope\n106\t  `code: forbidden` for a non-admin key.\n107\t- *Latency:* a single indexed PK upsert; see the Open Question for its budget.\n108\t\n109\t### `POST /v1/events` — the quota check (atomic, strict, replay-safe)\n110\t\n111\tThe existing service already branches on \"did this insert land a new row?\". The quota check slots\n112\t**exactly into the winning-insert branch**, which is what makes the three hardest requirements fall\n113\tout naturally:\n114\t\n115\t```\n116\tinsert_event_if_new(...)            # ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING (unchanged)\n117\t  ├─ returned a row (new event) ──► read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)   # NEW\n118\t  │                                   if quota exists and R + Q > L:  raise AppError(429, quota_exceeded)  # rolls back the event insert\n119\t  │                                 increment_usage_rollup(...)           # unchanged\n120\t  └─ returned None (replay)   ──►  find_event_by_idempotency_key(...) → 200 replay   # quota NEVER consulted\n121\t```\n122\t\n123\t1. **Idempotent replay never consults the quota** (brief: a retry of an accepted event must never\n124\t   flip to 429 and adds no usage) — because the check lives only on the `inserted is not None` branch;\n125\t   a duplicate `idempotency_key` takes the untouched replay path and returns the original 200.\n126\t2. **A rejected event leaves no trace** — the check runs *after* the event `INSERT` but *inside* the\n127\t   same `scoped_transaction`; raising `AppError` propagates out of the `session.begin()` context,\n128\t   which **rolls back**, undoing the event row and skipping the rollup increment. Usage is never\n129\t   incremented for a rejected event, and — because the event row is rolled back — a later retry of a\n130\t   *rejected* event is a fresh insert re-evaluated against the (possibly changed) quota, which is the\n131\t   correct semantics (a 429'd event was never accepted).\n132\t3. **`R + Q > L` is checked, including the empty window** — `R` defaults to 0 when no rollup row\n133\t   exists yet, so an event with `Q > L` against an empty window is rejected too (brief).\n134\t\n135\t#### The atomic read-and-decide (the strict-enforcement mechanism)\n136\t\n137\t- *What:* one repository function `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(session, api_key_id, customer_id,\n138\t  metric, window_start)` runs a single statement that reads the limit **and** the current rollup\n139\t  total while taking a row lock on the quota row:\n140\t\n141\t  ```sql\n142\t  SELECT q.limit_per_window,\n143\t         COALESCE(r.total_quantity, 0) AS current_total\n144\t  FROM quotas q\n145\t  LEFT JOIN usage_rollup r\n146\t    ON  r.api_key_id = q.api_key_id AND r.customer_id = q.customer_id\n147\t    AND r.metric = q.metric AND r.window_start = :window_start\n148\t  WHERE q.api_key_id = :api_key_id AND q.customer_id = :customer_id AND q.metric = :metric\n149\t  FOR UPDATE OF q\n150\t  ```\n151\t\n152\t  Returns `None` → **no quota → unlimited** (proceed to the normal upsert, zero extra locking).\n153\t  Returns a row → the service computes `current_total + Q > limit` and either raises or increments.\n154\t- *Why `FOR UPDATE` on the quota row (and why it is race-free):* strict enforcement is a\n155\t  **check-then-act** on a shared counter — the classic TOCTOU. The quota row is the natural\n156\t  serialization point because, in the enforced path, **it always exists** (a rollup row may not yet\n157\t  exist for a fresh window, so it cannot be the lock target). Every concurrent `POST` for the same\n158\t  `(customer, metric)` must acquire `FOR UPDATE OF q` on that one row first, so they **block on it\n159\t  until the holder commits/rolls back**. While the lock is held, no other writer can read `current_total`\n160\t  or increment the rollup, so the decision is made on an accurate value and the subsequent\n161\t  `increment_usage_rollup` is the only mutation until commit. Result: **usage can never exceed `L`**.\n162\t  Reading `current_total` via an unlocked `LEFT JOIN` is safe precisely because the rollup row is only\n163\t  ever written by holders of the quota lock.\n164\t- *Enabling conditions (so this is a verifiable mechanism, not a slogan):*\n165\t  - **Lock ordering is consistent → no deadlock:** every request acquires locks in the same order —\n166\t    the new event row (distinct `idempotency_key`, no cross-contention) → the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`)\n167\t    → the rollup row (`ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE`). Two posts for the same `(customer, metric)` contend\n168\t    only on the quota row, in that order, so no lock cycle can form.\n169\t  - **Fail-secure on reject:** the rollback is what enforces \"no partial write\"; the `AppError` is\n170\t    raised *before* `increment_usage_rollup`, so a rejected request commits nothing.\n171\t  - **Unlimited path takes no lock:** when the quota `WHERE` matches nothing, `FOR UPDATE` locks no\n172\t    row — customers without a quota add zero contention (only a single indexed lookup that returns 0\n173\t    rows). This is the common path and protects the p95 budget.\n174\t- *Why not the alternatives:*\n175\t  - A **single-statement CTE upsert with a `WHERE total + EXCLUDED <= limit` guard** was rejected: the\n176\t    decision sub-CTE reads a snapshot value while `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` re-reads the row at write\n177\t    time, so under READ COMMITTED two concurrent posts can both pass the snapshot check and jointly\n178\t    exceed `L` — it does **not** give strict enforcement, and the guard also cannot cleanly reject the\n179\t    *first* insert into an empty window (`Q > L`).\n180\t  - **`SERIALIZABLE` isolation** was rejected: it would force retry-loop handling on the hot ingest\n181\t    path and abort-storm under contention — heavier and less predictable than a targeted row lock.\n182\t  - **`pg_advisory_xact_lock(hash(customer,metric,window))`** was rejected: it serializes on exactly\n183\t    the right granularity but reasons over a hashed integer (collision handling, no visible row) and\n184\t    is less reviewable than locking the real quota row the brief itself suggests (\"row lock\").\n185\t- *Tradeoff accepted (brief-sanctioned):* posts to the **same quota'd `(customer, metric)`**\n186\t  serialize. Under realistic and load-test traffic (keys spread across many customers/metrics) this is\n187\t  near-zero contention; a single hot quota'd bucket serializes its writers, which is the price of\n188\t  \"usage never exceeds `L`\". The p95 < 50 ms budget is measured with quotas active (AC20).\n189\t\n190\t### The error-code facade extension (`quota_exceeded` vs `rate_limited`)\n191\t\n192\t- *Problem:* the error envelope maps status→code via `_STATUS_TO_CODE`, and **429 already maps to\n193\t  `rate_limited`** (the Tier-2 throttle). Quota rejection must be a *distinct* 429 code.\n194\t- *What / how:* add a small `AppError(HTTPException)` in `src/api/errors.py` carrying an explicit\n195\t  `app_code`, and have `handle_http_exception` prefer `getattr(exc, \"app_code\", None)` over the status\n196\t  map. `QuotaExceededError` is `AppError(429, app_code=\"quota_exceeded\", detail=\"metric quota exceeded\n197\t  for the current window\", headers={\"Retry-After\": <seconds to next hour>})`. The throttle's\n198\t  `HTTPException` still resolves to `rate_limited` (no `app_code`), so throttle-vs-quota precedence and\n199\t  codes are exactly as the brief requires.\n200\t- *Why not extend `_STATUS_TO_CODE`:* a status→code map cannot represent two codes sharing one status;\n201\t  a per-exception `app_code` is the minimal, single-boundary change that keeps the one-envelope facade.\n202\t- *`Retry-After`:* seconds until the next hour boundary = `(window_start + 1h) − received_at`, floored\n203\t  to `>= 1`; matches the throttle's existing header pattern. The body stays the three-field envelope\n204\t  `{code, message, requestId}` — **no usage/limit numbers** (brief; also an info-disclosure control).\n205\t\n206\t## Data / migrations\n207\t\n208\t### New/changed stored fields and their classification (data-protection)\n209\t\n210\t`data-protection-conventions` consulted. The brief classifies all new stored fields as **non-sensitive\n211\toperational config**, and that holds under the taxonomy:\n212\t\n213\t| Field | Table | Class | At-rest control |\n214\t|---|---|---|---|\n215\t| `customer_id` | `quotas` | non-sensitive (opaque tenant-assigned id, already stored in `events`/`usage_rollup`) | RDS SSE (storage-level) — no field-level crypto |\n216\t| `metric` | `quotas` | non-sensitive (opaque metric name, already stored) | RDS SSE |\n217\t| `limit_per_window` | `quotas` | non-sensitive (a business cap the admin itself sets) | RDS SSE |\n218\t| `scope` | `api_keys` | non-sensitive authorization metadata (not a credential; the credential is `secret_hash`, already Argon2id) | RDS SSE |\n219\t\n220\tNo field is `credential`, `sensitive-PII`, or `personal`, so **no field-level `data_protection`\n221\tmechanism (KDF/KMS) is required** — recorded here as an explicit classification so security's\n222\t`data_surface` reconciliation sees it declared. Storage-level encryption is the existing RDS SSE on\n223\tthe instance (unchanged; no new KMS key). *Note:* usage **totals** are treated as billing-adjacent by\n224\tthe existing code (`Cache-Control: no-store` on `/v1/usage`), which is why the quota **error body and\n225\tlogs deliberately omit usage/limit numbers** (see *Logging* and threat I1) — but the stored *config*\n226\tfields above are not themselves sensitive.\n227\t\n228\t### Migration `0003_create_quotas_and_api_key_scope.py` (one revision, expand-only)\n229\t\n230\tBoth expand-only changes land in **one** Alembic revision (brief: \"ONE expand-only migration\" now\n231\talso covers the `scope` column):\n232\t\n233\t- `CREATE TABLE quotas`:\n234\t  - `api_key_id BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES api_keys(id)`, `customer_id TEXT NOT NULL`,\n235\t    `metric TEXT NOT NULL`, `limit_per_window BIGINT NOT NULL`,\n236\t    `created_at`/`updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()`.\n237\t  - `PRIMARY KEY (api_key_id, customer_id, metric)` — the tenant-scoped natural key (one cap per\n238\t    customer/metric per tenant; the PK doubles as the upsert conflict target and the lookup index).\n239\t  - `CHECK (limit_per_window >= 1)` — a cap is `>= 1`, never 0 (a kill-switch is out of scope; the\n240\t    DB CHECK is the backstop behind the schema's `conint(ge=1)`).\n241\t  - `ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` + `CREATE POLICY quotas_tenant_isolation USING (api_key_id =\n242\t    current_setting('app.current_api_key_id', true)::bigint)` — mirrors `events`/`usage_rollup`.\n243\t    **RLS enabling condition (U-02):** this backstop is only effective if the application's DB role is\n244\t    **not the table owner** and lacks `BYPASSRLS` (a table owner bypasses non-`FORCE` RLS). The\n245\t    existing tables use `ENABLE` (not `FORCE`), implying the app already connects as a non-owner role;\n246\t    `quotas` mirrors that. The **primary** control is the explicit `api_key_id = :api_key_id` filter\n247\t    present in every `quotas` query; RLS is defense-in-depth. Verifying the app role is a non-owner (or\n248\t    adding `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY`) is called out as an Open Question.\n249\t- `ALTER TABLE api_keys ADD COLUMN scope TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'ingest'` +\n250\t  `CHECK (scope IN ('ingest','admin'))` — backfill-free (the `DEFAULT` applies to existing rows), so\n251\t  no data migration and safe on a live table.\n252\t- `downgrade()`: `DROP TABLE quotas`; `ALTER TABLE api_keys DROP COLUMN scope` (FK/constraint-safe).\n253\t\n254\t**Reversibility kind (audit E6 — asserted precisely by AC16):** this revision is *both* a\n255\tcreate-migration (`quotas`) and an expand on a populated table (`api_keys.scope`):\n256\t- `quotas` — **schema + constraints** reversibility only: `down` drops the table, so literal row\n257\t  survival across `down` is undefined by definition; `up→down→up` must restore the schema and\n258\t  re-enforce every PK/FK/CHECK identically.\n259\t- `api_keys.scope` — the pre-existing `api_keys` **rows survive** `up→down→up` (only a column is\n260\t  added/dropped; the other columns are untouched). The added `scope` column's *values* reset to the\n261\t  `'ingest'` default on `down` — that is the **defined expand/contract contract of an add-column**, not\n262\t  data loss of a populated business column. AC16 asserts row survival for the pre-existing columns and\n263\t  the constraint re-enforcement, and phrases the `scope` reset as expected.\n264\t\n265\tDDIA operability note: the migration is O(1) on schema plus a metadata-only column add with a constant\n266\tdefault (Postgres 11+ does not rewrite the table for a non-volatile default) — safe under live ingest,\n267\tconsistent with how `0002` reasons about deploy ordering.\n268\t\n269\t## Auth\n270\t\n271\t- `api_keys_repo.find_active_key_by_key_id` gains `scope` in its `SELECT` and `ApiKeyRecord`;\n272\t  `api_keys_repo.create_api_key` gains a `scope: str = \"ingest\"` parameter (defaulted so existing\n273\t  callers are unaffected).\n274\t- `AuthenticatedPrincipal` gains `scope: str = \"ingest\"` (defaulted → any direct construction in unit\n275\t  tests keeps working); `verify_api_key` populates it from the record. The verification cache stores\n276\t  the whole principal, so `scope` is cached with it — no cache-contract change.\n277\t- The `PUT /v1/quotas` route's composed dependency runs `require_api_key → enforce_tier2_rate_limit`\n278\t  then asserts `principal.scope == 'admin'`, else raises `HTTPException(403)` (envelope `forbidden`)\n279\t  and logs `quota.forbidden`. This is **function-level authorization** (ASVS 8.2.1) — the admin gate —\n280\t  layered over the **data-level** tenant isolation (ASVS 8.2.2/8.4.1) that the `api_key_id` scoping +\n281\t  RLS already provide on the quota rows.\n282\t- No new provider, token type, or MFA path — `auth-patterns`' third-party IdP flows are not in scope\n283\t  (this project uses API keys per `CLAUDE.md`). `seed_api_key.py` grows an `--admin` flag that sets\n284\t  `scope='admin'` at provisioning; the printed `mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` value is unchanged.\n285\t\n286\t## Infrastructure\n287\t\n288\tNo infrastructure change. The feature adds one table and one column to the existing RDS PostgreSQL\n289\tinstance via Alembic; it provisions no new AWS service, IAM role, security group, or `infra/`\n290\tresource, and introduces no new runtime secret. Encryption-at-rest for the new columns is the existing\n291\tRDS SSE. `iac-conventions` is therefore not triggered. (The `infra/` diffs in the working tree belong\n292\tto a different branch/feature and are out of scope here.)\n293\t\n294\t## Logging\n295\t\n296\tNew observable events, via the existing `structlog` facade (`get_logger(service=\"meterly\")`), OTel\n297\ttrace-id already propagated (`logging-conventions`):\n298\t\n299\t- `quota.upsert` (**INFO**) on a successful `PUT /v1/quotas` — `userId=<admin api_key_id>`,\n300\t  `action=\"create\"|\"replace\"`, `customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`, `requestId`. This is the\n301\t  **audit trail** for who set what cap when (repudiation / ASVS 16.2.1). `limit_per_window` is\n302\t  non-sensitive config the admin itself supplied, so it is safe (and useful) to log.\n303\t- `quota.rejected` (**WARNING**) on a 429 quota rejection — `userId`, `action=\"deny\"`, `customer_id`,\n304\t  `metric`, `reason=\"quota_exceeded\"`, `requestId`. **Deliberately omits `current_total`/`limit`** —\n305\t  usage totals are billing-adjacent (consistency with the `/v1/usage` `no-store` treatment and the\n306\t  brief's \"no usage numbers in error bodies\"); the enforcement event itself is what ops needs\n307\t  (ASVS 16.3.3 — security-control / business-limit enforcement).\n308\t- `quota.forbidden` (**WARNING**) on a non-admin `PUT /v1/quotas` — `userId`, `action=\"deny\"`,\n309\t  `reason=\"insufficient_scope\"`, `requestId` (ASVS 16.3.2 — failed authorization).\n310\t\n311\tAll three ride the existing PII-redaction and generic-error-envelope facade — no stack/SQL leaks to\n312\tthe client (ASVS 16.5.1/16.5.3).\n313\t\n314\t## API edge\n315\t\n316\t`api-edge-conventions` applied to the new HTTP surface:\n317\t- `PUT /v1/quotas` inherits the full edge stack by being mounted; it is a **per-owner resource**\n318\t  endpoint, so its rate limit is the **principal-keyed post-auth Tier-2** token bucket (shared\n319\t  `enforce_tier2_rate_limit`, keyed on `api_key_id`) — not the IP-keyed Tier-1 (that stays the pre-auth\n320\t  edge shed). The two-principals-one-IP discriminating shape from the existing `test_rate_limit.py`\n321\t  proves the key dimension (AC15).\n322\t- **CORS:** `configure_cors` currently allows `[\"GET\", \"POST\"]`; add `\"PUT\"` for correctness. (This is\n323\t  a server-to-server API with an empty origin allowlist, so CORS is effectively inert — the change is\n324\t  for completeness, not a live control.)\n325\t- The new 429 `quota_exceeded` + `Retry-After` follow the throttle's established header/envelope\n326\t  pattern; idempotency-key handling is unchanged (PUT is idempotent by method).\n327\t\n328\t## DAST readiness\n329\t\n330\t`dast-conventions`: the running app serves this new HTTP surface, so it must arrive scan-ready.\n331\t- **Served OpenAPI schema:** FastAPI auto-generates `/openapi.json` from the route + Pydantic schemas;\n332\t  `PUT /v1/quotas` and its `QuotaPutRequest`/`QuotaResponse` will appear automatically. AC21 asserts\n333\t  the path is present in the served schema so the scanner's spec matches the implemented route.\n334\t- **Seeded non-prod test user + auth context:** the endpoint is authenticated **and** admin-scoped, so\n335\t  the DAST auth context needs an **admin** test key. `seed_api_key.py --admin` provisions it in\n336\t  staging/local; the auth context stays `Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` (the\n337\t  existing DAST-3 context, still documented here so `test_dast_context_documented.py` stays green).\n338\t  AC21 records the admin test-key requirement.\n339\t\n340\t## Input surface (enumerated for security's `input_surface` reconciliation)\n341\t\n342\tEvery input source the feature exposes, with its planned controls (each PUT input also carries a\n343\tvalidation + a rate-limit acceptance criterion — see `acceptance.md`):\n344\t\n345\t1. **`PUT /v1/quotas` request body** (new): `customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`; unknown\n346\t   fields rejected (`extra='forbid'`). Validation contract in *Threat Model → Validation contracts*.\n347\t   Rate limit: Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` (post-auth, principal-keyed). → AC5 (validation) + AC15\n348\t   (rate-limit).\n349\t2. **`Authorization` header** (unchanged): the existing anchored split-token regex in\n350\t   `src/auth/api_key.py` — reused, not modified.\n351\t3. **`POST /v1/events` request body** (pre-existing input source, behavior extended not re-shaped):\n352\t   the existing `EventCreateRequest` contract and Tier-2 throttle remain the validation + rate-limit\n353\t   controls; the feature adds a **business-limit** (the quota) on top (ASVS 2.3.2/2.4.1), not a new\n354\t   input contract. Enumerated here so the surface is accounted for; no new input field is introduced.\n355\t\n356\t## Files affected\n357\t\n358\tCreate:\n359\t- `alembic/versions/0003_create_quotas_and_api_key_scope.py` — the one expand-only revision (quotas\n360\t  table + RLS policy; `api_keys.scope` column + CHECK).\n361\t- `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` — `QuotaPutRequest` (validation contract) + `QuotaResponse` (echo shape).\n362\t- `src/api/routes/quotas.py` — `PUT /v1/quotas` route + the admin-scope composed dependency.\n363\t- `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` — `upsert_quota` (xmax insert/replace) + `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` (the `FOR UPDATE` read-and-decide).\n364\t- `src/services/quota_service.py` — orchestrates the `PUT` upsert (transaction + 201/200 mapping + `quota.upsert` log).\n365\t- `tests/test_schemas_quotas.py` — unit: `limit>=1`, 0/negative/non-int → 422, `extra='forbid'`, customer/metric allowlist.\n366\t- `tests/integration/test_quotas_endpoint.py` — PUT create/replace, admin-scope 403, 401, validation 422, tenant isolation.\n367\t- `tests/integration/test_events_quota_enforcement.py` — `R+Q>L` 429, empty-window `Q>L`, unlimited passthrough, replay-over-quota 200, mid-window effect, rollback-no-partial, `Retry-After`, `quota_exceeded` code.\n368\t- `tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py` — strict enforcement: N concurrent distinct-key posts never exceed `L`.\n369\t- `tests/integration/test_quota_migration.py` — `0003` up→down→up schema+constraints round-trip; api_keys row survival.\n370\t- `tests/integration/k6/load_events_quota.js` — k6 driver for the quota-active ingest perf run (AC20).\n371\t\n372\tModify:\n373\t- `src/repositories/api_keys_repo.py` — `SELECT scope`; `ApiKeyRecord.scope`; `create_api_key(scope=…)`.\n374\t- `src/auth/api_key.py` — `AuthenticatedPrincipal.scope`; populate it in `verify_api_key`.\n375\t- `src/services/events_service.py` — insert the quota check on the winning-insert branch; `quota.rejected` log; raise `QuotaExceededError`.\n376\t- `src/api/errors.py` — add `AppError(HTTPException)` with `app_code`; honor `app_code` in `handle_http_exception`.\n377\t- `src/api/middleware.py` — add `\"PUT\"` to CORS `allow_methods`.\n378\t- `src/main.py` — mount `quotas_router`.\n379\t- `scripts/seed_api_key.py` — `--admin` flag → `scope='admin'`.\n380\t- `tests/integration/test_seed_api_key_script.py` — cover `--admin` sets `scope='admin'`; default `'ingest'`.\n381\t- `tests/integration/test_perf_k6_load.py` — quota-active ingest perf scenario (seed high quotas, run `load_events_quota.js`, record p95 vs the 50 ms budget).\n382\t- `docs/system_architecture.md` — quotas surface + the enforcement/atomicity note (also carries the `mtr_live`/`Bearer` DAST-3 context string).\n383\t- `src/api/README.md`, `src/services/README.md`, `src/repositories/README.md`, `src/auth/README.md` — per-directory doc updates for the touched modules.\n384\t- `CLAUDE.md` — note the `admin` scope + `PUT /v1/quotas` in the auth line (touched-surface doc).\n385\t\n386\t## Test strategy\n387\t\n388\t**`pyramid`** (the project default). Most coverage is unit — the validation schema\n389\t(`test_schemas_quotas.py`), the 201/200 upsert mapping, the `R+Q>L` decision boundary, and the\n390\t`Retry-After` computation are all pure/near-pure logic testable without a database. A **focused\n391\tintegration tier** against the real Postgres + Redis testcontainers (existing `conftest`) covers the\n392\tguarantees that are only real against actual Postgres — the `FOR UPDATE` strict-enforcement\n393\tconcurrency, the transaction rollback-no-partial, the RLS tenant isolation, and the migration\n394\tround-trip — matching how `events`/`usage` are already tested. One **perf** run (k6, existing harness)\n395\tmeasures the ingest p95 with quotas active. E2E stays minimal (the endpoint round-trips are covered at\n396\tthe integration tier). This is a bias toward the unit tier, not a relaxation of the coverage gate\n397\t(>= 85% branch coverage still required).\n398\t\n399\t## Open questions\n400\t\n401\t1. **PUT /v1/quotas latency budget** (the brief's single Open item). The stated p95 < 50 ms budget is\n402\t   for `POST /v1/events` only. *Proposed default:* **p95 < 100 ms** for `PUT /v1/quotas` as a\n403\t   documented target, **not** a load-tested AC — it is an admin-only, low-traffic route doing a single\n404\t   indexed upsert, so a sustained k6 load test would be over-engineering. Confirm at the checkpoint,\n405\t   or raise the budget to a hard AC if admin tooling is expected to batch-set quotas at volume.\n406\t2. **RLS enabling condition.** `quotas` mirrors the existing `ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` (not `FORCE`),\n407\t   which is only effective if the app's DB role is a **non-owner** of the table. *Proposed:* confirm\n408\t   the app role is a non-owner (the existing `events`/`usage_rollup` design already depends on this);\n409\t   if it is the owner, add `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` to `quotas` (and ideally the existing tables).\n410\t   The explicit `api_key_id` filter in every query is the primary control regardless.\n411\t3. **Admin = ingest superset (tenant model).** The plan models a quota-using tenant as **one\n412\t   admin-scoped key that both ingests and administers** (the only model under which enforcement binds\n413\t   with the current single-key-per-tenant schema). Confirm this is acceptable, or defer quotas until a\n414\t   multi-key-per-tenant model exists (larger; out of this slice's scope per the brief).\n415\t\n416\t## Threat Model\n417\t\n418\tMethod: STRIDE (Shostack), scoped to this feature. Each credible threat names a **concrete mechanism**\n419\t(library/config/SQL construct + the file it lives in) and the **ASVS 5.0.0** requirement it satisfies.\n420\t\n421\t### Assets and trust boundaries\n422\t\n423\tAssets: the `quotas` rows (per-tenant caps), the `api_keys.scope` authorization attribute, the\n424\t`usage_rollup` counters the check reads, the admin API key (`Argon2id`-hashed secret), and the\n425\t`PUT /v1/quotas` / `POST /v1/events` endpoints. Trust boundaries crossed: **client ↔ app** (public\n426\tinternet → ALB → FastAPI: unauthenticated bytes become an authenticated, scope-bearing principal) and\n427\t**app ↔ RDS** (the transaction that atomically checks the quota and increments the rollup). No new\n428\tservice↔service or cloud-control-plane boundary is introduced.\n429\t\n430\t### Validation contracts (per boundary input)\n431\t\n432\t| Input | Contract | Sink it protects | Lives in |\n433\t|---|---|---|---|\n434\t| `customer_id` (PUT body) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$')` (reused `CustomerId`) | `quotas` upsert + the quota-lookup SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n435\t| `metric` (PUT body) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,64}$')` (reused `Metric`) | `quotas` upsert + lookup SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n436\t| `limit_per_window` (PUT body) | `conint(ge=1, le=10**15)` (BIGINT-safe upper bound; 0/negative → 422) | BIGINT column + the `R+Q>L` comparison (overflow/absurd-value guard) | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n437\t| unknown PUT fields | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` | mass-assignment (no client-set `api_key_id`/`scope`) | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n438\t| `Authorization` header | existing anchored `^mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>$` regex | `api_keys` lookup | `src/auth/api_key.py` (unchanged) |\n439\t| `POST /v1/events` body | existing `EventCreateRequest` (unchanged) | events/rollup/quota SQL sinks | `src/api/schemas/events.py` (unchanged) |\n440\t\n441\tAll new SQL uses SQLAlchemy `text()` with **bound parameters only** — no string interpolation\n442\t(ASVS 1.2.4).\n443\t\n444\t### STRIDE table\n445\t\n446\t| Category | Asset / Boundary | Attack vector | Severity | Mitigation (mechanism + file) | ASVS req(s) |\n447\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n448\t| **Spoofing** | `PUT /v1/quotas` / client↔app | Unauthenticated or non-admin caller sets/changes a cap | High | `require_api_key` (Argon2id split-token) then an `admin`-scope assertion in the route's composed dependency raising `HTTPException(403)` — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` + `src/auth/api_key.py` | 6.2.x, 8.2.1 |\n449\t| **Tampering** | `quotas` SQL / client↔app | SQLi via `customer_id`/`metric` into the new quota queries | High | Anchored allowlist `constr` (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) + parameterized `text()` bind params (`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) | 1.2.4, 2.2.1 |\n450\t| **Tampering** | `quotas` / mass-assignment | Client sets `api_key_id`/`scope` via the PUT body to write another tenant's cap or self-elevate | High | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` on `QuotaPutRequest`; server sets `api_key_id` from the principal, `scope` is never a body field — `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py` | 15.3.3, 8.2.3 |\n451\t| **Tampering** | `usage_rollup` / app↔RDS | Concurrent posts race the check-then-increment so usage exceeds `L` (TOCTOU) | High | `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF q` on the quota row serializes all writers for a `(customer,metric)`; the check + `increment_usage_rollup` run in one `scoped_transaction`; a reject raises before the increment and the transaction rolls back (fail-secure). Enabling conditions: consistent lock order (event→quota→rollup) → no deadlock; unlimited path takes no lock — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `src/services/events_service.py` | 2.3.3, 2.3.4, 15.4.x |\n452\t| **Repudiation** | admin action / audit | Admin denies setting a blocking cap; client disputes a 429 | Medium | Structured `quota.upsert` (who/what/when incl. `limit_per_window`) and `quota.rejected` (`userId`,`customer_id`,`metric`,`requestId`) via the structlog facade; `requestId` ties the envelope to the log — `src/services/quota_service.py`, `src/services/events_service.py` | 16.2.1, 16.3.2, 16.3.3 |\n453\t| **Info Disclosure** | 429 body / client↔app | Error body/logs leak `current_total`/`limit`, letting a caller probe a competitor's usage | Medium | Envelope is the three-field `{code,message,requestId}` only — no usage/limit numbers (`_envelope` in `src/api/errors.py`); `quota.rejected` log omits totals; `customer_id`/`metric` travel in the PUT **body**, never the URL/query string (scope: body only) | 14.2.1, 15.3.1, 16.5.1 |\n454\t| **Info Disclosure** | quota data at rest | Cap/scope readable if the store is compromised | Low (accepted) | Classified non-sensitive operational config; existing RDS SSE (storage-level) covers it; no field-level crypto required — see *Data classification* | 14.1.x |\n455\t| **Denial of Service** | both endpoints | Request flood spends Argon2id verifies / DB work | Medium | Tier-1 IP+route pre-auth throttle (`Tier1EdgeThrottleMiddleware`, `/health` exempt, client IP from `request.client` behind the ALB) + Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` post-auth token bucket (`enforce_tier2_rate_limit`) on the new route + 8 KiB body guard — `src/api/middleware.py`, `src/auth/rate_limit.py` | 2.4.1, 4.x, 15.2.2 |\n456\t| **Denial of Service** | `usage_rollup` hot row | The `FOR UPDATE` lock serializes a hot quota'd bucket, spiking latency | Medium (accepted) | Lock scoped to the quota row so only quota'd `(customer,metric)` serialize; bounded 2-statement critical section; p95 measured under load with quotas active (AC20) — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` | 15.4.x |\n457\t| **Denial of Service** | `limit_per_window` | Absurd/overflowing limit value | Low | `conint(ge=1, le=10**15)` + BIGINT column — `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` | 2.2.1 |\n458\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | `PUT /v1/quotas` (function-level) | `ingest` key calls the admin route | High | `principal.scope == 'admin'` gate → `HTTPException(403)`; `quota.forbidden` logged — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` | 8.2.1 |\n459\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | `quotas` (data-level / cross-tenant) | A key reads/writes/enforces another tenant's cap (IDOR/BOLA) | High | Every `quotas` query filters `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id`; `quotas_tenant_isolation` RLS policy via `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` in `scoped_transaction`. Enabling condition: RLS effective only if the app role is a non-owner (else `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY`) — see Open Question 2 — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `alembic/versions/0003_*`, `src/db/session.py` | 8.2.2, 8.4.1 |\n460\t\n461\t### Accepted risks / out of scope\n462\t\n463\t- **Same-bucket serialization latency** (DoS row-2) is accepted as the cost of strict enforcement\n464\t  (brief-sanctioned); measured, not eliminated.\n465\t- **Quota data at rest** relies on RDS SSE only (non-sensitive classification) — no field-level crypto.\n466\t- **Removing/unsetting a quota, `GET /v1/quotas`, kill-switch (`limit=0`), global/cross-tenant quotas,\n467\t  deferred effectiveness, per-quota windows** — all out of scope per the brief; not modeled.\n468\t- **Multi-key-per-tenant** (a separate ingest key + admin key sharing one tenant) is not supported\n469\t  this slice (Open Question 3); quotas bind to a single `api_key_id`.\n470\t\n471\t### Threat-model diagram (Mermaid DFD)\n472\t\n473\t```mermaid\n474\tflowchart TD\n475\t    admin[Admin/Ingest API client]:::ext\n476\t    subgraph edge[Trust boundary: public edge - ALB to FastAPI]\n477\t        t1(Tier-1 IP throttle + body guard)\n478\t        auth(require_api_key + Tier-2 throttle)\n479\t        scope(admin-scope gate):::warn\n480\t        put(PUT /v1/quotas handler)\n481\t        post(POST /v1/events handler)\n482\t        check(quota check + rollup increment - one txn):::warn\n483\t    end\n484\t    subgraph rds[Trust boundary: app to RDS Postgres]\n485\t        keys[(api_keys + scope)]\n486\t        quotas[(quotas)]\n487\t        rollup[(usage_rollup)]\n488\t        events[(events)]\n489\t    end\n490\t    redis[(Redis token buckets)]\n491\t\n492\t    admin -- HTTPS: Bearer mtr_live_key -->|body: customer_id,metric,limit| t1\n493\t    t1 -- rate ok --> auth\n494\t    auth -. verify Argon2id .-> keys\n495\t    auth -. token bucket .-> redis\n496\t    auth --> scope\n497\t    scope -- scope=admin --> put\n498\t    auth --> post\n499\t    put -- upsert under principal.api_key_id --> quotas\n500\t    post -- insert event --> events\n501\t    post --> check\n502\t    check -- FOR UPDATE OF q --> quotas\n503\t    check -- read R / increment --> rollup\n504\t\n505\t    classDef ext fill:#eee,stroke:#333;\n506\t    classDef warn fill:#ffe0b2,stroke:#b71c1c,stroke-width:2px;\n507\t```\n508\t\n509\t⚠ high-risk nodes: the **admin-scope gate** (Spoofing/EoP) and the **quota check + rollup increment\n510\tsingle transaction** (Tampering/TOCTOU).\n511\t\n512\t### Copy-paste visualization prompt\n513\t\n514\t```text\n515\tBuild a threat-model visualization for this feature (Meterly per-customer metric quotas).\n516\t\n517\tASSETS: quotas rows (per-tenant caps: api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window);\n518\tapi_keys.scope authorization attribute; usage_rollup hourly counters; events log; the admin API\n519\tkey (Argon2id-hashed split token); the PUT /v1/quotas and POST /v1/events HTTP endpoints.\n520\t\n521\tTRUST BOUNDARIES: (1) client <-> app: public internet -> ALB -> FastAPI, where unauthenticated\n522\tbytes become an authenticated, scope-bearing principal; (2) app <-> RDS PostgreSQL: the single\n523\ttransaction that atomically checks the quota (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE on the quota row) and\n524\tincrements the rollup.\n525\t\n526\tSTRIDE THREATS (threat; vector; severity; mitigation + concrete mechanism):\n527\t- Spoofing; unauthenticated/non-admin caller sets a cap; HIGH; require_api_key (Argon2id split\n528\t  token) + admin-scope assertion raising HTTP 403 in the PUT route dependency.\n529\t- Tampering; SQL injection via customer_id/metric; HIGH; anchored allowlist constr + parameterized\n530\t  SQLAlchemy text() bind params only.\n531\t- Tampering; mass-assignment of api_key_id/scope via the PUT body; HIGH; Pydantic extra='forbid';\n532\t  server sets api_key_id from the principal; scope is never a request field.\n533\t- Tampering; concurrent posts race the check-then-increment so usage exceeds the cap L (TOCTOU);\n534\t  HIGH; SELECT ... FOR UPDATE OF the quota row serializes writers; check + increment in one\n535\t  transaction; reject raises before increment and the transaction rolls back (no partial write);\n536\t  consistent lock order event->quota->rollup avoids deadlock.\n537\t- Repudiation; admin denies setting a blocking cap / client disputes a 429; MEDIUM; structured\n538\t  quota.upsert (who/what/when) and quota.rejected (userId, customer_id, metric, requestId) logs.\n539\t- Information disclosure; 429 body or logs leak current usage/limit; MEDIUM; three-field envelope\n540\t  {code,message,requestId} only, no usage numbers; logs omit totals; identifiers in body not URL.\n541\t- Denial of service; request flood; MEDIUM; Tier-1 IP throttle + Tier-2 per-api_key_id token\n542\t  bucket + 8 KiB body guard.\n543\t- Denial of service; FOR UPDATE serializes a hot quota'd bucket; MEDIUM (accepted); lock scoped to\n544\t  the quota row so only quota'd buckets serialize; p95 measured under load.\n545\t- Elevation of privilege; ingest key calls the admin route; HIGH; scope=='admin' gate -> HTTP 403.\n546\t- Elevation of privilege; a key reads/writes another tenant's cap (IDOR/BOLA); HIGH; every query\n547\t  filters api_key_id = principal.api_key_id; RLS policy quotas_tenant_isolation via SET LOCAL\n548\t  app.current_api_key_id (effective only if the app DB role is a non-owner, else FORCE RLS).\n549\t\n550\tRender this as an OWASP Threat Dragon diagram. Output either (a) valid Threat Dragon JSON\n551\timportable at app.threatdragon.com, or (b) a labeled data flow diagram with trust boundaries if\n552\tJSON is not feasible. No additional context is available beyond what is in this prompt.\n553\t```\n554\t\n555\t## ASVS Compliance\n556\t\n557\tOWASP ASVS 5.0.0. **L1 + L2 are universal** for every triggered chapter; in-scope **L3** is listed\n558\twith justification. Requirement IDs are cited per threat in the STRIDE table above.\n559\t\n560\t**Triggered chapters:** V1 (encoding/parameterized SQL), V2 (validation + business-logic limit +\n561\ttransactional atomicity + anti-automation), V4 (API surface), V6 (API-key authentication), V8\n562\t(authorization — the admin gate + tenant isolation; the high-priority IDOR/BOLA chapter), V12 (TLS —\n563\tsatisfied by existing ALB/RDS TLS, unchanged), V13 (config — docs off in prod, secrets in\n564\tmanager — existing), V14 (data protection — no sensitive data in URL; non-sensitive classification),\n565\tV15 (secure coding — minimal response fields, mass-assignment, safe concurrency), V16 (logging + error\n566\thandling).\n567\t\n568\t**`n/a`:** V3 (server-to-server API, no browser HTML/cookies; CORS handled under V4/edge), V5 (no file\n569\thandling), V7 (no sessions — stateless API keys), V9 (no JWT/self-contained tokens), V10 (no OAuth/OIDC),\n570\tV11 (no **new** crypto surface — existing Argon2id `11.4.2` key hashing and CSPRNG `11.5.1` key\n571\tgeneration are unchanged), V17 (no WebRTC).\n572\t\n573\t**In-scope L3:**\n574\t- **V15.4.x — safe concurrency / TOCTOU-atomic check-then-act.** Justification: billing/usage\n575\t  integrity is breach-critical for a metering product — \"usage never exceeds `L`\" is the feature's\n576\t  core correctness guarantee, delivered by the `FOR UPDATE` quota-row lock + single-transaction\n577\t  check-then-increment.\n578\t- **V11.2.4 — constant-time comparison.** Already in scope for the auth verification cache\n579\t  (unchanged); noted for continuity.\n580\t\n581\t**Waivers:** none for triggered L1/L2 code/config items (the feature's surface is covered by the\n582\tmechanisms above). Chapter `X.1` documentation items are advisory (org-level), not blocking.\n583\t\n584\t## Acceptance criteria trace (PROJECT.md / CLAUDE.md \"What done means\")\n585\t\n586\t- **Smoke check passes** → ✓ *Backend* / *Infrastructure*: no change to `/health` or app startup; the\n587\t  new route mounts on the existing app; deferred DB/Redis init preserved.\n588\t- **Security report clean** → ✓ *Threat Model* + *ASVS Compliance* (parameterized SQL, admin gate,\n589\t  tenant isolation/RLS, strict-enforcement concurrency, generic error envelope); AC18, AC22.\n590\t- **Tests pass at >= 85% coverage** → ✓ *Test strategy* + `acceptance.md` (every AC maps to a named\n591\t  test; unit-heavy pyramid, integration for the Postgres-only guarantees).\n592\t- **Docs updated for touched directories** → ✓ *Files affected* (system_architecture.md + per-dir\n593\t  READMEs + CLAUDE.md).\n594\t- **PR description written** → handled by the documentation stage (out of planning's hands; noted).\n595\t"}]},"uuid":"7cbb0f88-db58-4daa-a89f-ab37d7e57b7c","timestamp":"2026-07-09T23:00:16.890Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bbb2cff6-f6b5-42eb-9874-ab961403c8ef","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
