{"parentUuid":"1f593681-b3f2-4d3e-ac10-35ca6a887a07","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0fbc342a4e25e60d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcsLJABEwCyrLB43DDDoS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PiWFM7584MPeP5ni38on2d","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4715,"cache_read_input_tokens":156594,"output_tokens":838,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4715},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":838,"cache_read_input_tokens":156594,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4715,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4715,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcsLJ8oPiFhFkejAXPjFD","attributionAgent":"planning","type":"assistant","uuid":"bce71e27-65a7-492e-b59c-59f24e1c9f5c","timestamp":"2026-07-09T23:15:00.265Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
{"parentUuid":"bce71e27-65a7-492e-b59c-59f24e1c9f5c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"895b7771-0494-4fd1-9c42-d5085f2ef142","agentId":"a0fbc342a4e25e60d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PiWFM7584MPeP5ni38on2d","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Plan — quota administration (list + delete)\n2\t\n3\tAuthoritative brief: `.pipeline/requirements.md` (operator-elicited; Resolved / Open / Out-of-scope).\n4\tEvery Resolved item below is turned into scope + an acceptance criterion; the brief has **zero Open\n5\titems** (the operator confirmed the defaults explicitly), and the Out-of-scope items are hard\n6\texclusions that are **not** planned. Design source: none (backend HTTP API — no UI to build).\n7\t\n8\t## Summary\n9\t\n10\tMeterly already lets an admin-scoped key create-or-replace a per-customer, per-metric usage cap via\n11\t`PUT /v1/quotas` (feature \"metric-quotas\", shipped). This feature completes the quota-admin CRUD by\n12\tadding the two read/remove surfaces on the **same path**, gated by the **same** admin dependency\n13\tchain and scoped to the **same** tenant model:\n14\t\n15\t1. **`GET /v1/quotas`** (new, admin-scoped) — returns the full, unpaginated list of the caller's own\n16\t   tenant's quotas, deterministically ordered by `(customer_id, metric)`, each row the minimal\n17\t   `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` field set (identical to the existing `QuotaResponse`).\n18\t2. **`DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`** (new, admin-scoped) — removes the cap for one\n19\t   `(customer_id, metric)` in the caller's tenant. **204 No Content** on success; **404** (standard\n20\t   error envelope) when no such quota exists in the caller's tenant (explicit, not silently\n21\t   idempotent). Query parameters only, no request body.\n22\t\n23\tThe core approach is **extend, don't reinvent**: reuse the `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency\n24\t(auth → Tier-2 throttle → admin-scope gate), reuse the exact anchored `CustomerId`/`Metric`\n25\tallowlists PUT already validates against, reuse `scoped_transaction` (which sets the RLS session\n26\tsetting), and reuse the `quotas` table and its `quotas_tenant_isolation` FORCE-RLS policy that\n27\tmigration `0003` already installed. No new table, **no new Alembic migration**, no new cloud\n28\tinfrastructure, no new credential, and — critically — **no change to `POST /v1/events`**: deleting a\n29\tquota removes only the cap, never touching recorded `usage_rollup` usage. The scanner/auth context\n30\tstays the existing `Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` split-token.\n31\t\n32\tWhy this is a genuine micro-change and not a rewrite: every layer already exists and already isolates\n33\tby `api_key_id`. GET adds one ordered `SELECT`; DELETE adds one parameterized `DELETE … RETURNING`;\n34\tboth hang off the existing route module and its existing admin dependency. The only net-new\n35\tcorrectness surfaces are (a) the DELETE-not-found → 404 decision and (b) the query-param validation\n36\tcontract for DELETE — both covered explicitly below and in the threat model.\n37\t\n38\t## Stack notes\n39\t\n40\tAssessed each default against this project; every choice **endorses the existing Meterly stack**\n41\trecorded in `CLAUDE.md`. This is a brownfield increment onto a shipped feature, so consistency with\n42\tthe established stack is the overriding consideration and each default already fits — there is no\n43\tdivergence for the checkpoint to ratify, only the confirmation below.\n44\t\n45\t- **Language / framework:** Python 3.12 + FastAPI + async SQLAlchemy `text()` repositories — endorsed\n46\t  (matches every existing module and the sibling `PUT /v1/quotas` code this extends).\n47\t- **Database:** PostgreSQL (RDS) — endorsed; the feature reads and deletes rows in the existing\n48\t  `quotas` table using boring, proven primitives (`SELECT … ORDER BY`, `DELETE … RETURNING`). DDIA\n49\t  note: no new storage/messaging surface, so no replication/partitioning/consistency question arises\n50\t  — this is single-node transactional CRUD on an existing indexed table.\n51\t- **Migrations:** Alembic — endorsed, **but not exercised**: no schema change, so **no new revision**.\n52\t  The `quotas` table, its PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`, its `CHECK`, and its FORCE-RLS\n53\t  policy all already exist from revision `0003`. Adding a migration here would be dead DDL.\n54\t- **Auth:** existing API-key facade + the `scope` column (`ingest`/`admin`) — endorsed and reused\n55\t  unchanged. Both new routes reuse the existing `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency verbatim; no\n56\t  new scope, provider, token type, or MFA path.\n57\t- **Cloud / IaC:** AWS + Terraform — **no change**. The feature provisions nothing (`iac-conventions`\n58\t  not triggered — no `infra/` resource). It reads/deletes rows in the existing RDS instance.\n59\t- **Observability / logging:** structlog facade + CloudWatch/X-Ray + Sentry — endorsed; the feature\n60\t  emits **one** new structured event (`quota.delete`) and reuses the existing `quota.forbidden`.\n61\t- **Runtime secrets:** unchanged — no new credential consumed (`secrets-management` not triggered).\n62\t\n63\t## Backend\n64\t\n65\t### `GET /v1/quotas` — the tenant's full quota list\n66\t\n67\t- *What:* a new handler on the existing `src/api/routes/quotas.py` router,\n68\t  `@router.get(\"/v1/quotas\", response_model=list[QuotaResponse])`, depending on the existing\n69\t  `_require_admin_and_throttled`. It calls a new service `list_tenant_quotas(principal)` that opens a\n70\t  `scoped_transaction(principal.api_key_id)` and calls a new repository `list_quotas(session,\n71\t  api_key_id)`, returning `list[QuotaResponse]`.\n72\t- *Why full/unpaginated (not paginated or filtered):* the brief resolves this explicitly — per-tenant\n73\t  quota counts are expected to stay small (bounded by the admin's own `PUT` calls, one row per\n74\t  `(customer, metric)`), so pagination/filtering would be speculative machinery for a set that fits in\n75\t  one response. Pagination is a hard out-of-scope exclusion. Rejected alternative — a\n76\t  `limit`/`offset` or cursor scheme — adds an input surface, an ordering-stability contract across\n77\t  pages, and tests, for zero benefit at the expected cardinality.\n78\t- *Why `response_model=list[QuotaResponse]` (the minimal field set):* the response echoes only\n79\t  `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` — never `api_key_id`, `created_at`, or `updated_at`. This\n80\t  is the same minimal-exposure contract the brief pins and that `QuotaResponse` already encodes\n81\t  (ASVS 14.3.x / minimal response — threat **I1**). Returning the raw `quotas` row would leak the\n82\t  internal `api_key_id` and timestamps. FastAPI serializes the list through `QuotaResponse`, so the\n83\t  field projection is enforced by the framework, not by hand.\n84\t- *Why deterministic `ORDER BY customer_id, metric`:* the brief requires deterministic ordering. The\n85\t  repository issues `SELECT customer_id, metric, limit_per_window FROM quotas WHERE api_key_id =\n86\t  :api_key_id ORDER BY customer_id, metric`. `ORDER BY` on the two PK-prefix columns gives a stable,\n87\t  repeatable order every call (and is index-friendly — the PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`\n88\t  already orders exactly this way, so the sort is effectively free). Rejected alternative — relying on\n89\t  physical/heap order — is non-deterministic and would make the \"deterministic\" requirement\n90\t  unverifiable. (Collation note in Open Question 2.)\n91\t- *Empty set → `200 []`, never 404:* a caller with no quotas gets an empty JSON array with 200, the\n92\t  same \"absence is not an error\" semantics `GET /v1/usage` already uses (a zeroed bucket returns 200,\n93\t  not 404). A missing *collection* is an empty list; only a missing *addressed resource* (the DELETE\n94\t  target) is a 404.\n95\t\n96\t### `DELETE /v1/quotas` — remove one cap, explicitly\n97\t\n98\t- *What:* a new handler `@router.delete(\"/v1/quotas\",\n99\t  status_code=status.HTTP_204_NO_CONTENT)` taking the two identifiers as **query parameters** through\n100\t  a new `QuotaDeleteParams` schema (`Annotated[QuotaDeleteParams, Query()]`, mirroring\n101\t  `GET /v1/usage`'s `UsageQueryParams`), depending on `_require_admin_and_throttled`. It calls a new\n102\t  service `delete_tenant_quota(principal, params)` → new repository `delete_quota(session, api_key_id,\n103\t  customer_id, metric)`. On success the handler returns `Response(status_code=204)` (empty body).\n104\t- *Why query params, not a body (DELETE semantics):* the brief resolves this. `DELETE` addresses a\n105\t  resource; the resource identity is `(customer_id, metric)`. Putting the identity in the query string\n106\t  keeps `DELETE` bodyless (many proxies/clients drop or ignore DELETE bodies) and mirrors how\n107\t  `GET /v1/usage` already addresses a `(customer_id, metric, window)` resource via query params. The\n108\t  params reuse the **exact same** anchored allowlists PUT uses (`CustomerId`, `Metric` already defined\n109\t  at module scope in `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) — same identifiers, same sinks, same rejection\n110\t  behavior (422). Rejected alternative — a JSON body on DELETE — diverges from the `GET /v1/usage`\n111\t  addressing pattern and relies on body support that DELETE clients do not guarantee.\n112\t- *Why 404-on-absent, not idempotent-204 (the one real decision here):* the brief resolves that a\n113\t  delete of a non-existent quota returns **404 with the standard error envelope**, not a silent 204 —\n114\t  \"deletes are explicit, not silently idempotent.\" The repository's `DELETE … WHERE api_key_id = :…\n115\t  AND customer_id = :… AND metric = :… RETURNING customer_id` returns a row iff exactly one matched;\n116\t  the service maps \"no row returned\" → `HTTPException(404, \"quota not found\")`, which the error facade\n117\t  renders as `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"not_found\", …}}` (404 is already in `_STATUS_TO_CODE`). No new error\n118\t  code is needed. Tradeoff accepted: a client that retries a successful DELETE gets a 404 on the\n119\t  second call — that is the brief-sanctioned explicit-delete contract, and it is the honest signal\n120\t  (\"there was nothing here to delete\"), distinguishable from a wrong-tenant delete only in that both\n121\t  correctly refuse to act.\n122\t- *Why 204 No Content on success:* the resource is gone; there is nothing meaningful to return, and\n123\t  echoing the deleted cap would invite treating DELETE as a read. 204 with an empty body is the\n124\t  idiomatic REST result and what the brief pins.\n125\t- *Tenant confinement is structural, not a special case:* the `DELETE` `WHERE` clause filters\n126\t  `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id` (the primary control), and it runs inside `scoped_transaction`,\n127\t  which `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` so the `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS policy\n128\t  (migration `0003`) is the backstop. Because the policy's `USING` predicate hides other tenants'\n129\t  rows, a cross-tenant DELETE matches **zero** rows and therefore returns 404 — a wrong-tenant delete\n130\t  is indistinguishable from a truly-absent quota, which is exactly the desired BOLA-safe behavior\n131\t  (threat **E2** — DELETE cannot even *see* another tenant's row to remove it).\n132\t\n133\t### DELETE racing in-flight `POST /v1/events` (explicitly no extra synchronization)\n134\t\n135\tThe brief resolves that a DELETE racing an in-flight ingest enforcement is **acceptable** and requires\n136\tno special synchronization. Concretely: `POST /v1/events` reads the quota with `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF\n137\tq` inside its own transaction. A DELETE and an ingest for the same `(customer, metric)` contend on\n138\tthat same row lock, so PostgreSQL serializes them — one commits first. If the DELETE commits first,\n139\tsubsequent ingests read \"no quota\" and are unlimited; ingests that had already read the (old) cap\n140\tbefore the DELETE committed may still be enforced against it. This is the **same replacement race PUT\n141\talready has** and is correct: the delete takes effect for everything that reads after it commits. We\n142\tadd **no** advisory lock, no serialization barrier, and no usage reset — all three are hard\n143\tout-of-scope exclusions. The DELETE's own row lock (implicit in the `DELETE`) plus the ingest's\n144\t`FOR UPDATE` are sufficient for a consistent commit order; there is no torn state.\n145\t\n146\t## Data / migrations\n147\t\n148\t**No migration, no schema change, no new stored field.** GET reads existing rows; DELETE removes\n149\texisting rows. The `quotas` table, its constraints, and its FORCE-RLS policy already exist (revision\n150\t`0003`). Therefore:\n151\t\n152\t- No file is added under `alembic/versions/` (asserted negatively by AC14).\n153\t- **No `data_protection` criterion is emitted.** No field is *stored* by this feature; the rows it\n154\t  reads/deletes were already classified **non-sensitive operational config** in the metric-quotas plan\n155\t  (`customer_id`/`metric`/`limit_per_window` are opaque operational identifiers/config, already at\n156\t  rest under RDS SSE). Recorded explicitly so security's `data_surface` reconciliation sees the\n157\t  waiver: `data_protection_waiver: this feature stores no new field; the quota rows it lists/deletes\n158\t  are pre-classified non-sensitive operational config already covered by RDS SSE (storage-level) — no\n159\t  field-level KDF/KMS applies`.\n160\t- No migration-reversibility criterion is emitted (no migration to reverse).\n161\t\n162\t## Auth\n163\t\n164\tNo auth change. Both new routes reuse the **existing** `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency in\n165\t`src/api/routes/quotas.py` verbatim — the same composed chain PUT uses: `require_api_key` (Argon2id\n166\tsplit-token) → `enforce_tier2_rate_limit` (per-`api_key_id` throttle) → the `scope == 'admin'` gate\n167\t(→ `HTTPException(403)` + `quota.forbidden` log). This is **function-level authorization** (ASVS\n168\t8.2.1 — the admin gate) layered over **data-level** tenant isolation (ASVS 8.2.2/8.4.1 — the\n169\t`api_key_id` scoping + FORCE RLS on every `quotas` query). No new scope, provider, token, or MFA path;\n170\t`auth-patterns`' third-party IdP flows remain out of scope (this project uses API keys per\n171\t`CLAUDE.md`). GET is admin-only by the brief (no ingest-scoped read path — a hard exclusion).\n172\t\n173\t## Infrastructure\n174\t\n175\tNo infrastructure change. The feature provisions no AWS service, IAM role, security group, or `infra/`\n176\tresource, and introduces no runtime secret. It reads/deletes rows in the existing RDS PostgreSQL\n177\tinstance. `iac-conventions` is not triggered.\n178\t\n179\t## Logging\n180\t\n181\tVia the existing `structlog` facade (`get_logger(service=\"meterly\")`), OTel trace-id already\n182\tpropagated (`logging-conventions`). The facade already redacts `customer_id` (personal-data class) and\n183\tstrips control characters centrally — call sites never redact ad hoc.\n184\t\n185\t- **`quota.delete` (INFO)** — new; emitted by `delete_tenant_quota` on a successful 204:\n186\t  `userId=<admin api_key_id>`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id` (auto-redacted to `***redacted***` by\n187\t  the facade), `metric`, `requestId`. This is the **audit trail** for who removed which cap when —\n188\t  un-capping a customer is a security-relevant business action (it re-enables overage), so it must be\n189\t  attributable (repudiation / ASVS 16.2.1). This mirrors the existing `quota.upsert` field shape.\n190\t- **`quota.forbidden` (WARNING)** — reused unchanged; a non-admin key hitting GET or DELETE trips the\n191\t  existing scope gate, which already logs this (`userId`, `action=\"deny\"`,\n192\t  `reason=\"insufficient_scope\"`) — ASVS 16.3.2.\n193\t\n194\t**GET listing is deliberately not given a dedicated business log** — it is a read of the caller's own\n195\tconfiguration, following the `GET /v1/usage` precedent (plain reads emit no business audit event; the\n196\trequest-context middleware already carries the per-request trace). Flagged as Open Question 1 for the\n197\tcheckpoint to confirm. No log line carries usage totals or a raw `customer_id` (the facade guarantees\n198\tthe latter).\n199\t\n200\t## API edge\n201\t\n202\t`api-edge-conventions` applied to the two new HTTP surfaces:\n203\t\n204\t- **Rate limiting:** both routes are **per-owner resource** endpoints, so they inherit the\n205\t  **principal-keyed post-auth Tier-2** token bucket (via `_require_admin_and_throttled` →\n206\t  `enforce_tier2_rate_limit`, keyed on `api_key_id`) — not the IP-keyed Tier-1 (that stays the\n207\t  pre-auth edge shed, inherited by mounting). The two-principals-one-IP discriminating shape proves\n208\t  the key dimension (AC12).\n209\t- **CORS:** `configure_cors` currently allows `[\"GET\", \"POST\", \"PUT\"]`; add `\"DELETE\"` for correctness\n210\t  (`GET` is already allowed). As with the PUT addition, this is a server-to-server API with an empty\n211\t  origin allowlist, so CORS is effectively inert — the change is for completeness, not a live control.\n212\t- **Error envelope:** DELETE-not-found raises a plain `HTTPException(404)`, which the existing\n213\t  `handle_http_exception` facade maps to `{\"error\":{\"code\":\"not_found\",\"message\":…,\"requestId\":…}}`.\n214\t  No `AppError`/`app_code` extension is needed (unlike the quota `429`) because 404 already has a\n215\t  distinct code in `_STATUS_TO_CODE`. The 204 success path returns an empty body through the FastAPI\n216\t  `Response`.\n217\t- **Body-size guard / Tier-1 throttle / security headers:** inherited unchanged by being mounted.\n218\t\n219\t## DAST readiness\n220\t\n221\t`dast-conventions`: the running app serves these two new HTTP surfaces, so they must arrive scan-ready.\n222\t\n223\t- **Served OpenAPI schema:** FastAPI auto-generates `/openapi.json` from the routes + Pydantic schemas;\n224\t  `GET /v1/quotas` and `DELETE /v1/quotas` (with `QuotaDeleteParams` and the `list[QuotaResponse]` /\n225\t  `204` responses) appear automatically. AC17 asserts both verbs are present under `/v1/quotas` in the\n226\t  served schema so the scanner's spec matches the implemented routes (not hand-drifted).\n227\t- **Seeded non-prod test user + auth context:** both endpoints are authenticated **and** admin-scoped,\n228\t  so the DAST auth context needs the **admin** test key. `seed_api_key.py --admin` (existing)\n229\t  provisions it in staging/local; the auth context stays `Authorization: Bearer\n230\t  mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` — the existing DAST-3 context, documented here so\n231\t  `test_dast_context_documented.py` stays green (it greps the plan/docs for `mtr_live` + `Bearer`).\n232\t\n233\t## Input surface (enumerated for security's `input_surface` reconciliation)\n234\t\n235\tEvery input source the feature exposes, with its planned controls:\n236\t\n237\t1. **`GET /v1/quotas`** — accepts **no** body/query/path parameter (full list, no filter/pagination —\n238\t   a hard exclusion). Its only input is the reused, unchanged `Authorization` header. **Validation\n239\t   AC: N/A** (no request parameter to validate). **Rate-limit:** Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` (reused) →\n240\t   AC12. Authorization/scope covered by AC4; auth by AC5.\n241\t2. **`DELETE /v1/quotas` query parameters** (new): `customer_id`, `metric`; unknown query params\n242\t   rejected (`extra='forbid'`). **Validation AC (non-waivable):** AC9. **Rate-limit:** Tier-2\n243\t   per-`api_key_id` (reused) → AC12.\n244\t3. **`Authorization` header** (unchanged): the existing anchored split-token regex in\n245\t   `src/auth/api_key.py` — reused, not modified.\n246\t\n247\tNo queue/message consumer, file/CSV ingest, form, or webhook receiver is introduced.\n248\t\n249\t## Files affected\n250\t\n251\tModify (source + tests — the implementation change set):\n252\t- `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` — add `QuotaDeleteParams` (query-param contract; reuse the module-level\n253\t  `CustomerId`/`Metric`; `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')`). `QuotaResponse` reused unchanged for GET rows.\n254\t- `src/api/routes/quotas.py` — add the `GET` (list) and `DELETE` handlers; both depend on the existing\n255\t  `_require_admin_and_throttled`.\n256\t- `src/services/quota_service.py` — add `list_tenant_quotas(principal)` (read + map to\n257\t  `list[QuotaResponse]`) and `delete_tenant_quota(principal, params)` (delete, raise 404 if absent,\n258\t  emit `quota.delete`).\n259\t- `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` — add `list_quotas(session, api_key_id)` (ordered, `api_key_id`-\n260\t  scoped `SELECT`) and `delete_quota(session, api_key_id, customer_id, metric)` (parameterized\n261\t  `DELETE … RETURNING`, returns whether a row matched).\n262\t- `src/api/middleware.py` — add `\"DELETE\"` to the CORS `allow_methods` list.\n263\t- `tests/test_schemas_quotas.py` — unit tests for `QuotaDeleteParams` (allowlist accept/reject,\n264\t  injection/oversized rejection, `extra='forbid'`).\n265\t\n266\tCreate:\n267\t- `tests/integration/test_quotas_list_delete.py` — integration tests for GET (order, minimal fields,\n268\t  empty→`200 []`, tenant isolation, ingest-key 403, no-auth 401) and DELETE (204 + row removed, 404\n269\t  absent, cross-tenant→404 + victim row intact, validation 422, ingest-key 403, no-auth 401,\n270\t  `quota.delete` logged), the Tier-2 two-principals-one-IP shape, the no-usage-reset / no-events-change\n271\t  guarantee, and the OpenAPI presence of both verbs.\n272\t\n273\tDocs (handled at the documentation stage, per the \"docs updated for touched directories\"\n274\tdone-criterion — not part of the implementation change set):\n275\t- `docs/system_architecture.md` — add the GET/DELETE quota-admin surface (also carries the\n276\t  `mtr_live`/`Bearer` DAST-3 context string).\n277\t- `src/api/README.md`, `src/services/README.md`, `src/repositories/README.md` — per-directory updates\n278\t  for the touched modules.\n279\t- `CLAUDE.md` — note `GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas` alongside the existing `PUT` in the auth line.\n280\t\n281\t**Task decomposition:** the implementation change set is **7 files** (6 modified + 1 created source/\n282\ttest files above; docs are a separate stage). That is below the ≥8-file threshold, so **no\n283\t`tasks.md`** is emitted — this builds single-shot from `plan.md`, extending existing modules with a\n284\trepo function pair, a service function pair, two route handlers, and one query-param schema.\n285\t\n286\t## Test strategy\n287\t\n288\t**`pyramid`** (the project default). The unit tier carries the boundary logic that needs no database:\n289\t`QuotaDeleteParams` validation (allowlist, injection/oversized rejection, `extra='forbid'`) in\n290\t`tests/test_schemas_quotas.py`, and the 404-vs-204 decision is a thin mapping best proven end-to-end.\n291\tA **focused integration tier** against the real Postgres + Redis testcontainers (existing `conftest`)\n292\tcovers the guarantees that are only real against actual Postgres — deterministic ordering over a\n293\tseeded multi-row set, the empty-list case, tenant isolation for both GET and DELETE (the FORCE-RLS\n294\tbackstop + `api_key_id` filter), the DELETE 204/404 contract, the two-principals-one-IP throttle\n295\tdimension, and the \"delete removes the cap but never resets `usage_rollup`, and `POST /v1/events`\n296\tun-caps cleanly\" cross-behavior. E2E stays minimal (the route round-trips are the integration tier).\n297\tThis is a bias toward exercising the real datastore for the tenancy/ordering guarantees, still under\n298\tthe unchanged `>= 85%` branch-coverage gate — not a relaxation of it.\n299\t\n300\t## Open questions\n301\t\n302\t1. **GET list read-logging.** The plan emits **no** dedicated business-audit log for `GET /v1/quotas`\n303\t   (a read of the caller's own config; mirrors `GET /v1/usage`, which logs no business event). DELETE\n304\t   *is* logged (`quota.delete`). *Proposed default:* keep GET unlogged. Confirm at the checkpoint, or\n305\t   add a light `quota.list` INFO (count only, no `customer_id`) if admin-read auditing is desired.\n306\t2. **Ordering collation.** `ORDER BY customer_id, metric` yields a **deterministic** order every call\n307\t   (the requirement), using the RDS default text collation. *Proposed default:* do not add\n308\t   `COLLATE \"C\"` — the requirement is *deterministic* order (guaranteed by `ORDER BY`), not\n309\t   byte-identical order across differing collations, and there is a single RDS collation in this\n310\t   deployment. Confirm, or add `COLLATE \"C\"` if cross-environment byte-stable ordering is later\n311\t   required.\n312\t\n313\t## Threat Model\n314\t\n315\tMethod: STRIDE (Shostack), scoped to **this feature** (GET list + DELETE). Each credible threat names\n316\ta **concrete mechanism** (library/config/SQL construct + the file it lives in) and the **ASVS 5.0.0**\n317\trequirement it satisfies. Most controls are **reused, already-verified** mechanisms from the shipped\n318\tmetric-quotas feature; the net-new surfaces are the DELETE query-param contract and the DELETE-not-\n319\tfound path.\n320\t\n321\t### Assets and trust boundaries\n322\t\n323\tAssets: the `quotas` rows (now *readable* via GET and *removable* via DELETE), the `api_keys.scope`\n324\tauthorization attribute, the `usage_rollup` counters (which DELETE must **not** touch), the admin API\n325\tkey (Argon2id-hashed secret), and the `GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas` endpoints. Trust boundaries crossed:\n326\t**client ↔ app** (public internet → ALB → FastAPI: unauthenticated bytes become an authenticated,\n327\tscope-bearing principal) and **app ↔ RDS** (the scoped transaction that lists or deletes a tenant's\n328\trows). No new service↔service or cloud-control-plane boundary is introduced.\n329\t\n330\t### Validation contracts (per boundary input)\n331\t\n332\t| Input | Contract (type + bound + allowlist) | Sink it protects | Lives in |\n333\t|---|---|---|---|\n334\t| `customer_id` (DELETE query) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$')` (reused module `CustomerId`); anchored allowlist, ReDoS-safe | the `DELETE … WHERE customer_id = :customer_id` SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n335\t| `metric` (DELETE query) | `constr(pattern=r'^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,64}$')` (reused module `Metric`); anchored allowlist | the `DELETE … WHERE metric = :metric` SQL | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n336\t| unknown DELETE query params | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` on `QuotaDeleteParams` | mass-assignment / no client-set `api_key_id` | `src/api/schemas/quotas.py` |\n337\t| `GET /v1/quotas` | no request parameter accepted (no body/query/path) — no injectable input | n/a (only the `api_key_id`-scoped list `SELECT`) | `src/api/routes/quotas.py` |\n338\t| `Authorization` header | existing anchored `^mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>$` regex | `api_keys` lookup | `src/auth/api_key.py` (unchanged) |\n339\t\n340\tAll new SQL (the list `SELECT` and the `DELETE`) uses SQLAlchemy `text()` with **bound parameters\n341\tonly** — no string interpolation (ASVS 1.2.4).\n342\t\n343\t### STRIDE table\n344\t\n345\t| Category | Asset / Boundary | Attack vector | Severity | Mitigation (mechanism + file) | ASVS req(s) |\n346\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n347\t| **Spoofing** | GET/DELETE `/v1/quotas` / client↔app | Unauthenticated or non-admin caller lists or deletes caps | High | Reused `_require_admin_and_throttled`: `require_api_key` (Argon2id split-token) then a `scope == 'admin'` assertion raising `HTTPException(403)` — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` + `src/auth/api_key.py` | 6.2.x, 8.2.1 |\n348\t| **Tampering** | DELETE SQL / client↔app | SQLi via `customer_id`/`metric` query params into the new `DELETE` | High | Anchored allowlist `constr` on `QuotaDeleteParams` (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) rejects at the boundary (422) + parameterized `text()` bind params in `delete_quota` (`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) — payload never reaches the sink | 1.2.4, 2.2.1 |\n349\t| **Tampering** | DELETE params / mass-assignment | Client injects an extra query param (e.g. `api_key_id`) to widen the delete | Medium | `ConfigDict(extra='forbid')` on `QuotaDeleteParams`; `api_key_id` is set server-side from the principal, never a query param — `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py` | 15.3.3, 8.2.3 |\n350\t| **Repudiation** | admin delete / audit | Admin denies removing a cap (un-capping a customer re-enables overage) | Medium | Structured `quota.delete` INFO (`userId`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id` [facade-redacted], `metric`, `requestId`) via the structlog facade; `requestId` ties the 204/404 response to the log line — `src/services/quota_service.py` | 16.2.1 |\n351\t| **Info Disclosure** | GET response / client↔app | List leaks internal fields (`api_key_id`, timestamps) or another tenant's caps | High | `response_model=list[QuotaResponse]` projects only `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` (FastAPI-enforced); the list `SELECT` filters `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id` + FORCE-RLS backstop — `src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `alembic/versions/0003_*` | 14.3.x, 8.2.2 |\n352\t| **Info Disclosure** | DELETE query string | `customer_id`/`metric` in the URL query string may land in ALB/proxy access logs | Low (accepted) | Mirrors the existing `GET /v1/usage` query-param contract (the caller's *own* opaque identifiers); app-side structured logs **redact** `customer_id` via the logging facade; ALB access-log exposure of a caller's own id is a pre-existing, accepted risk — `src/logging/__init__.py` | 14.3.x |\n353\t| **Denial of Service** | both endpoints | Request flood spends Argon2id verifies / DB work | Medium | Reused Tier-1 IP+route pre-auth throttle (`Tier1EdgeThrottleMiddleware`, `/health` exempt, client IP from `request.client` behind the ALB) + Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` post-auth token bucket (`enforce_tier2_rate_limit`) on both routes — `src/api/middleware.py`, `src/auth/rate_limit.py` | 2.4.1, 4.x |\n354\t| **Denial of Service** | GET list size | Unpaginated list grows expensive if a tenant accumulates many quotas | Low (accepted) | Per-tenant quota counts are bounded by admin `PUT` volume (brief: \"expected to stay small\"); the `SELECT` is a PK-prefix-ordered index scan scoped to one `api_key_id`; Tier-2 throttle bounds call rate — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` | 4.x |\n355\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | GET/DELETE (function-level) | `ingest`-scoped key calls the admin-only routes | High | Reused `scope == 'admin'` gate → `HTTPException(403)`; `quota.forbidden` logged — `src/api/routes/quotas.py` | 8.2.1 |\n356\t| **Elevation of Privilege** | `quotas` (data-level / IDOR/BOLA) | A key lists or **deletes** another tenant's cap | High | Every `quotas` query filters `api_key_id = :principal.api_key_id`; `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS policy via `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id` in `scoped_transaction`. **Enabling condition (U-02):** `quotas` is owned by the `meterly_app` role, so `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` (already set in migration `0003`) is required and present — a table owner bypasses non-FORCE RLS. A cross-tenant DELETE therefore matches zero rows → 404 (cannot see or remove another tenant's row) — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`, `src/db/session.py`, `alembic/versions/0003_*` | 8.2.2, 8.4.1 |\n357\t| **Tampering** | `usage_rollup` integrity | DELETE resets/corrupts recorded usage, or races ingest into torn state | Medium (accepted) | `delete_quota` issues **only** a `DELETE` on `quotas` — it never touches `usage_rollup` (no usage reset, a hard exclusion). The DELETE's implicit row lock and the ingest's `SELECT … FOR UPDATE OF q` serialize on the same quota row, giving a consistent commit order without added synchronization (brief-accepted) — `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` | 2.3.x |\n358\t\n359\t### Accepted risks / out of scope\n360\t\n361\t- **DELETE-vs-ingest race** is accepted with **no** added synchronization (brief): the shared row lock\n362\t  yields a consistent commit order; enforcement stops for everything that reads after the delete\n363\t  commits, matching PUT-replacement semantics. Not a concurrency-integrity guarantee this slice.\n364\t- **`customer_id` in the DELETE query string** (Low): consistent with the existing `GET /v1/usage`\n365\t  query-param design; app logs redact it; ALB access-log exposure of a caller's own id is accepted.\n366\t- **Unpaginated GET list size** (Low): accepted on the brief's \"counts stay small\" assumption; Tier-2\n367\t  throttle + index scan bound it.\n368\t- **Quota data at rest** relies on RDS SSE (non-sensitive classification) — no field-level crypto;\n369\t  this feature stores no new field.\n370\t- **Hard exclusions not modeled:** pagination/filtering on GET, ingest-scoped read of quotas,\n371\t  including usage/remaining in the list, usage reset on delete, any `POST /v1/events` behavior change,\n372\t  and blocking/serializing delete against ingest — all out of scope per the brief.\n373\t\n374\t### Threat-model diagram (Mermaid DFD)\n375\t\n376\t```mermaid\n377\tflowchart TD\n378\t    admin[Admin API client]:::ext\n379\t    subgraph edge[Trust boundary: public edge - ALB to FastAPI]\n380\t        t1(Tier-1 IP throttle + body guard)\n381\t        auth(require_api_key + Tier-2 throttle)\n382\t        scope(admin-scope gate):::warn\n383\t        getq(GET /v1/quotas handler)\n384\t        delq(DELETE /v1/quotas handler):::warn\n385\t    end\n386\t    subgraph rds[Trust boundary: app to RDS Postgres - RLS FORCE]\n387\t        keys[(api_keys + scope)]\n388\t        quotas[(quotas)]\n389\t        rollup[(usage_rollup - untouched)]\n390\t    end\n391\t    redis[(Redis token buckets)]\n392\t\n393\t    admin -- HTTPS Bearer mtr_live_key -->|DELETE query customer_id,metric| t1\n394\t    t1 -- rate ok --> auth\n395\t    auth -. verify Argon2id .-> keys\n396\t    auth -. token bucket .-> redis\n397\t    auth --> scope\n398\t    scope -- scope=admin --> getq\n399\t    scope -- scope=admin --> delq\n400\t    getq -- SELECT api_key_id-scoped ORDER BY --> quotas\n401\t    delq -- DELETE api_key_id-scoped RETURNING --> quotas\n402\t    delq -. never writes .-x rollup\n403\t\n404\t    classDef ext fill:#eee,stroke:#333;\n405\t    classDef warn fill:#ffe0b2,stroke:#b71c1c,stroke-width:2px;\n406\t```\n407\t\n408\t⚠ high-risk nodes: the **admin-scope gate** (Spoofing/EoP) and the **DELETE handler** (cross-tenant\n409\tIDOR/BOLA — mitigated by the `api_key_id` filter + FORCE RLS, so a wrong-tenant delete matches zero\n410\trows → 404).\n411\t\n412\t### Copy-paste visualization prompt\n413\t\n414\t```text\n415\tBuild a threat-model visualization for this feature (Meterly quota administration: list + delete).\n416\t\n417\tASSETS: quotas rows (per-tenant caps: api_key_id, customer_id, metric, limit_per_window), now\n418\treadable via GET and removable via DELETE; api_keys.scope authorization attribute; usage_rollup\n419\thourly counters (which DELETE must NOT touch); the admin API key (Argon2id-hashed split token); the\n420\tGET /v1/quotas and DELETE /v1/quotas HTTP endpoints.\n421\t\n422\tTRUST BOUNDARIES: (1) client <-> app: public internet -> ALB -> FastAPI, where unauthenticated bytes\n423\tbecome an authenticated, admin-scope-bearing principal; (2) app <-> RDS PostgreSQL: the scoped\n424\ttransaction that lists or deletes a tenant's quota rows, with a FORCE row-level-security policy\n425\t(quotas_tenant_isolation) as the backstop behind the explicit api_key_id filter.\n426\t\n427\tSTRIDE THREATS (threat; vector; severity; mitigation + concrete mechanism):\n428\t- Spoofing; unauthenticated/non-admin caller lists or deletes caps; HIGH; reused\n429\t  _require_admin_and_throttled = require_api_key (Argon2id split token) + admin-scope assertion\n430\t  raising HTTP 403.\n431\t- Tampering; SQL injection via customer_id/metric DELETE query params; HIGH; anchored allowlist\n432\t  constr on QuotaDeleteParams rejects at the boundary (422) + parameterized SQLAlchemy text() bind\n433\t  params only.\n434\t- Tampering; extra query param to widen the delete (mass-assignment); MEDIUM; Pydantic\n435\t  extra='forbid'; api_key_id set server-side from the principal, never a query param.\n436\t- Repudiation; admin denies removing a cap (un-capping re-enables overage); MEDIUM; structured\n437\t  quota.delete INFO log (userId, action=delete, customer_id [redacted], metric, requestId).\n438\t- Information disclosure; GET leaks internal fields or another tenant's caps; HIGH;\n439\t  response_model=list[QuotaResponse] minimal field set + api_key_id-scoped SELECT + FORCE RLS.\n440\t- Information disclosure; customer_id/metric in the DELETE query string may reach access logs; LOW\n441\t  (accepted); mirrors GET /v1/usage; app logs redact customer_id; ALB log exposure of own id\n442\t  accepted.\n443\t- Denial of service; request flood; MEDIUM; reused Tier-1 IP throttle + Tier-2 per-api_key_id token\n444\t  bucket + body-size guard.\n445\t- Denial of service; unpaginated GET list grows expensive; LOW (accepted); per-tenant counts stay\n446\t  small; PK-prefix index scan scoped to one api_key_id; Tier-2 throttle bounds call rate.\n447\t- Elevation of privilege; ingest-scoped key calls the admin-only routes; HIGH; scope=='admin' gate\n448\t  -> HTTP 403.\n449\t- Elevation of privilege; a key lists or deletes another tenant's cap (IDOR/BOLA); HIGH; every query\n450\t  filters api_key_id = principal.api_key_id; FORCE RLS quotas_tenant_isolation via SET LOCAL\n451\t  app.current_api_key_id (FORCE required because meterly_app owns the table) -> cross-tenant DELETE\n452\t  matches zero rows -> 404.\n453\t- Tampering; DELETE resets usage or races ingest into torn state; MEDIUM (accepted); delete_quota\n454\t  only DELETEs quotas, never touches usage_rollup; shared row lock with the ingest FOR UPDATE gives\n455\t  a consistent commit order without added synchronization.\n456\t\n457\tRender this as an OWASP Threat Dragon diagram. Output either (a) valid Threat Dragon JSON importable\n458\tat app.threatdragon.com, or (b) a labeled data flow diagram with trust boundaries if JSON is not\n459\tfeasible. No additional context is available beyond what is in this prompt.\n460\t```\n461\t\n462\t## ASVS Compliance\n463\t\n464\tOWASP ASVS 5.0.0. **L1 + L2 are universal** for every triggered chapter; in-scope **L3** is listed\n465\tbelow. Requirement IDs are cited per threat in the STRIDE table above.\n466\t\n467\t**Triggered chapters:** V1 (encoding / parameterized SQL — the DELETE `text()` bind params), V2\n468\t(validation — the `QuotaDeleteParams` contract + anti-automation Tier-2 throttle), V4 (API surface —\n469\ttwo new verbs on `/v1/quotas`), V6 (API-key authentication — reused), V8 (authorization — the admin\n470\tgate + tenant isolation on read/delete; **the priority chapter for this slice** given DELETE's\n471\tcross-tenant BOLA risk), V12 (TLS — existing ALB/RDS TLS, unchanged), V13 (config — docs off in prod,\n472\tsecrets in manager — existing), V14 (data protection — minimal GET response, no sensitive data\n473\tstored), V16 (logging + error handling — `quota.delete` audit, generic 404 envelope).\n474\t\n475\t**`n/a`:** V3 (server-to-server API, no browser HTML/cookies), V5 (no file handling), V7 (no\n476\tsessions — stateless API keys), V9 (no JWT/self-contained tokens), V10 (no OAuth/OIDC), V11 (no new\n477\tcrypto surface — Argon2id key hashing unchanged), V15 (no new concurrency-integrity guarantee — the\n478\tDELETE-vs-ingest race is an explicitly accepted risk, not an enforced invariant this slice), V17 (no\n479\tWebRTC).\n480\t\n481\t**In-scope L3:**\n482\t- **V8.2.x — object-level authorization rigor (IDOR/BOLA).** Justification: DELETE is a destructive\n483\t  cross-tenant-sensitive operation on a multi-tenant store; \"a key can neither see nor delete another\n484\t  tenant's quota\" is breach-critical for a metering product, delivered by the `api_key_id` filter +\n485\t  FORCE RLS and proven by the cross-tenant-DELETE→404 integration test (AC8).\n486\t\n487\t**Waivers:** none for triggered L1/L2 code/config items (the feature's surface is covered by the\n488\treused mechanisms above). Chapter `X.1` documentation items are advisory (org-level), not blocking.\n489\t\n490\t## Acceptance criteria trace (PROJECT.md / CLAUDE.md \"What done means\")\n491\t\n492\t- **Smoke check passes** → ✓ *Backend* / *Infrastructure*: no change to `/health` or app startup; the\n493\t  new handlers mount on the existing router; deferred DB/Redis init preserved.\n494\t- **Security report clean** → ✓ *Threat Model* + *ASVS Compliance* (parameterized DELETE SQL, admin\n495\t  gate, read/delete tenant isolation + FORCE RLS, minimal GET response, generic 404 envelope); AC9,\n496\t  AC15, AC18.\n497\t- **Tests pass at >= 85% coverage** → ✓ *Test strategy* + `acceptance.md` (every AC maps to a named\n498\t  test; unit for the schema contract, integration for the Postgres-only ordering/tenancy guarantees).\n499\t- **Docs updated for touched directories** → ✓ *Files affected* (system_architecture.md + per-dir\n500\t  READMEs + CLAUDE.md, at the documentation stage).\n501\t- **PR description written** → handled by the documentation stage (out of planning's hands; noted).\n502\t- **pipeline-ci green (required merge check)** → ✓ *CI*: this feature adds no workflow and no new job;\n503\t  it must keep the existing `pipeline-ci.yml` jobs (lint, tests+coverage, security scan) green. The\n504\t  new tests run under the same suite; no CI configuration change is planned.\n505\t"}]},"uuid":"b4e17a8f-0b84-48cf-a93d-fce0243dee34","timestamp":"2026-07-09T23:15:00.383Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bce71e27-65a7-492e-b59c-59f24e1c9f5c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
